### \[2022\] SGMC 67

Criminal Law – Offences – Section 9(1)(e) Remote Gambling Act 2014 (No. 34 of 2014)

Criminal Law – Offences – Section 16(2) Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309, Revised Edition 2011)

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9206/2022/01.\]

15 November 2022

### District Judge James Elisha Lee:

## Introduction

1       The Accused, Mr Wilfred Yap Wei Chieh, a 29-year-old Singaporean, pleaded guilty to one charge of assisting in the conduct of unlawful gambling under s 9(1)(e) of the Remote Gambling Act 2014 (No. 34 of 2014) (“RGA”) and 5 charges of possession for sale / selling components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product under s 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309, Revised Edition 2011) (“TCASA”). He also consented to having 10 other charges under the Tobacco Act taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (“TIC”). These were, namely, 2 counts of possession, other than for the purpose of sale, an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product under s 16(2A)(2), 5 counts of possession for sale articles designed to resemble a tobacco product under s 16(1)(a) and 3 counts of possession for sale components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product under s 16(2).

2       The prescribed punishment for the offence under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA is a fine of not less than $20,000 and not more than $200,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 5 years or to both. The prescribed punishment for the offence under s 16(2) of the TCASA is a fine not exceeding $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 6 months or to both.

4       The total sentence was therefore **2 weeks’ imprisonment and total fine of $28,000 in default 4 weeks and 32 days’ imprisonment**. The Accused being dissatisfied filed an appeal against his sentence. He is on bail pending appeal.

5       These are the grounds for the sentence imposed.

## The Charges

6       The proceeded charge under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA read as follows:

> **MAC-900260-2022**

> You … are charged that you, from sometime in October 2020 until 22 June 2021, in Singapore, did assist in the conduct of unlawful remote gambling, in accordance with arrangements by your principal, “Johnny”, to wit, by placing bets on behalf of approximately 2 punters and issuing a betting account to one Yap Seow Hong Joseph, thereby facilitating the commission of offences under s 8 of the Remote Gambling Act 2014 by punters, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under s 9(1)(e) of the Remote Gambling Act 2014.

7       The 5 proceeded charges under s 16(2) of the TCASA read as follows:

> **MSC-900084-2022**

> You … are charged that you, on 22 June 2021 between 12.55 am and 3.10 am at the open carpark of Block 320 Hougang Avenue 5, Singapore, did possess for sale components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product, to wit, 16 boxes (containing 48 pieces) of e-cigarette pods, being components required to assemble an imitation tobacco product, and you have thereby contravened section 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309) and committed an offence punishable under section 16(5)(a) of the same Act.

> **MCN-900086-2022**

> You … are charged that you, on 10 June 2021, Singapore, did sell components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product, to wit, three boxes (containing nine pieces) of ecigarette pods, being components required to assemble an imitation tobacco product, to one “Marcus”, and you have thereby contravened section 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309) and committed an offence punishable under section 16(5)(a) of the same Act.

> **MCN-900088-2022**

> You … are charged that you, on 19 May 2021, at Block 320 Hougang Avenue 5, Singapore, did sell components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product, to wit, 14 boxes (containing 42 pieces) of e-cigarette pods, being components required to assemble an imitation tobacco product, to one “Daniel”, and you have thereby contravened section 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309) and committed an offence punishable under section 16(5)(a) of the same Act.

> **MCN-900091-2022**

> You … are charged that you, on 9 June 2021, Singapore, did sell components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product, to wit, 21 boxes (containing 63 pieces) of e-cigarette pods, being components required to assemble an imitation tobacco product, to one “Shawn”, and you have thereby contravened section 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309) and committed an offence punishable under section 16(5)(a) of the same Act.

> **MSC-900095-2022**

> You … are charged that you, on 9 June 2021, Singapore, did sell components of an article that is designed to resemble a tobacco product, to wit, 10 boxes (containing 30 pieces) of e-cigarette pods, being components required to assemble an imitation tobacco product, to one “Julian”, and you have thereby contravened section 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act (Chapter 309) and committed an offence punishable under section 16(5)(a) of the same Act.

## Statements of Facts

8       The Statements of Facts (“SOF”) which the Accused admitted without qualification were as follows.

> **_Facts in respect of MAC-900260-2022_**

> **Introduction**

> 1.    The accused is Wilfred Yap Wei Chieh, a 29-year-old (DOB: 11 December 1992) male Singapore citizen (NRIC No: SXXX).

> **Arrest**

> 2.    On 22 June 2021, at about 1am, a party of police officers raided the accused’s residence in Singapore and placed him under arrest.

> **Background**

> 3.    Sometime in 2020, the accused was drinking with one “Andy”. The accused told “Andy” that he wanted to have an account for unlawful 4D remote gambling and asked whether “Andy” could introduce him to anyone. “Andy” informed the accused that he knew of an unlawful 4D remote gambling operator known as “Johnny”. The accused told “Andy” to ask “Johnny” to contact him, which “Johnny” subsequently did.

> 4.    Investigations revealed that “Johnny” was conducting unlawful remote gambling services in Singapore. “Johnny’s” unlawful remote gambling websites included “shen33”. This website provided 4D remote gambling services and was not provided by an exempt operator or a person otherwise exempt under s 40 of the Remote Gambling Act 2014 (“RGA”). “Johnny” operated an unlawful remote gambling syndicate and had several syndicate members operating under him.

> **Facts pertaining to the 1st charge (MAC-900260-2022)**

> 5.    Sometime in October 2020, “Johnny” offered the accused an agent account for “shen33” and informed him that the accused would earn 10% of the total bet value collected, and 5% of the total prize money if any of his punters won. The accused accepted “Johnny’s” offer, and “Johnny” issued an agent account to the accused for “shen33”.

> 6.    Thereafter, the accused operated his agent account from sometime in October 2020 until 22 June 2021 in accordance with arrangements by “Johnny” (the accused’s principal). The accused charged $1.60 for a “big” ticket and $0.70 for a “small” ticket.

> 7.    The accused had approximately 2 punters that would call or message the accused to ask him to place bets for them. The accused would then key in the bets using his agent account. From these 2 punters, the accused would earn a profit based on the commission rates set out at \[5\]. However, the exact amount of profit earned by the accused can no longer be determined at this stage. In particular, in relation to these 2 punters, on 22 June 2021, the accused stated to the Police that: “I do not wish to disclose their identity”.

> 8.    The accused also issued a betting account to one Yap Seow Hong Joseph, the accused’s father. For this betting account that the accused issued, the Police were only able to recover the bet value for 9 to 23 June 2021, which amounted to S$418.10. In relation to his father, the accused waived the profit that he would have otherwise earned.

> 9.    The accused would also hand over the bet monies to a runner of “Johnny” on various occasions.

> 10.    The accused’s actions facilitated several individuals in committing offences under s 8 of the RGA. 11. By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed an offence punishable under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA.

> **_Facts in respect of MSC-900084-2022 and 4 Ors_**

> 1.    The accused is Wilfred Yap Wei Chieh, male / 29 years old, D.O.B. 11 December 1992 (NRIC No. XXX). At the material time, he was residing at Blk 320 Hougang Ave 5, #XXX Singapore 530320 (“the Flat”).

> 2.    On 22 June 2021, between 12.55 am and 3.10 am, police officers recovered an assortment of imitation tobacco products from the Flat and the accused’s vehicle bearing registration number SJJ956X (“the Car”) which was parked at the open carpark of Blk 320 Hougang Ave 6.

> Facts relating to MSC- 900084-2022

> 3.    Investigations revealed that the accused was peddling imitation tobacco products. The accused admitted ownership to the 16 boxes of e-cigarette pod (3 pods per box) containing a total of 48 pods recovered from the Car and that they were meant for sale.

> 4.    Investigations also revealed that the accused had sold e-cigarette pods in Singapore in the following instances:

>> a.    On 10 June 2021, the accused sold 03 boxes of e-cigarette pods (3 pods per box) containing a total of 09 pods to one “Marcus” \[MSC-900086-2022\];

>> b.    On 19 May 2021, the accused sold 14 boxes of e-cigarette pods (3 pods per box) containing a total of 42 pods to one “Daniel” \[MSC-900088-2022\];

>> c.    On 9 June 2021, the accused sold 21 boxes of e-cigarette pods (3 pods per box) containing a total of 63 pods to one “Leon”\[ MSC-900091-2022\];

>> d.    On 9 June 2021, the accused sold 10 boxes of e-cigarette pods (3 pods per box) containing a total of 30 pods to one “Julian” \[MSC-900095-2022\].

> 5.    An e-cigarette pod is a component of an imitation tobacco product. It is an offence to sell and possess for sale a component of an imitation tobacco product in Singapore.

> 6.    By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has contravened s 16(2) of the Tobacco (Control of Advertisements and Sale) Act, (Chapter 309, 2011 Rev Ed) (“TCASA”) and committed 5 counts of an offence punishable under s 16(5)(a) of the TCASA.

> 7.    The accused admits to the offences and stands charged.

## Antecedents

9       The Accused is untraced.

## Prosecution’s Address on Sentence

### MAC-900260-2022

10     The Prosecution applied the sentencing framework as set out in the case of _PP v Khoo Moy Seen_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 98</span> (“Khoo Moy Seen”) in respect of the charge under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA and submitted for a sentence of **4 weeks’ imprisonment and fine of $20,000**.

11     In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court laid down a five-step sentencing framework for the offence under s 9(1) of the RGA which was adapted from the framework promulgated by CJ Menon in _Koo Kah Yee v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] 3 SLR 1440</span> for offences under s 11(1) of the RGA. The five-step process as set out in _Khoo Moy Seen_ is as follows:

> (a)     identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender;

> (b)     identify the indicative sentencing band, having regard to the levels of harm and culpability;

> (c)     identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range;

> (d)     make adjustments for offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors; and

> (e)     make further adjustments to take into account the totality principle.

12     The sentencing ranges are as follows:

![](data:image;base64,)

13     Applying the framework to the present case, the Prosecution submitted that the present case fell under slight harm and low culpability in view of the low bet value and number of punters involved. The Prosecution noted that in _Khoo Moy Seen_, where the accused had pleaded guilty to a charge under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA which involved 15 punters and a total bet value of $12,010.40, the High Court had assessed the level of harm to be in the middle of the low range and the level of culpability, based on the facts of the case, to be on the higher end of the low range, and held that the indicative starting sentence would be a fine of at least $20,000 and 3 months’ imprisonment. Drawing guidance from the case, the Prosecution submitted that the appropriate indicative starting sentence should be 4 weeks’ imprisonment[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1).

14     The Prosecution noted the High Court’s position in _Khoo Moy Seen_ that a fine in addition to the imprisonment term would be necessary to negate the profits that would have been earned from remote gambling activities. The Prosecution further noted that in _Khoo Moy Seen_, the Court had imposed the fine of $20,000 even though the estimated profit earned was only about $1,000. The Prosecution submitted, as such, that the prescribed minimum fine of $20,000 would be appropriate as although the actual profit earned by the accused could not be quantified, it was clear that the accused had earned profits[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2).

15     In their reply to the mitigation plea, the Prosecution further submitted that the accused’s refusal to disclose the identities of the 2 punters betting through him (see paragraph 7 of the Statement of Facts in respect of MAC 900260-2022) had prevented further investigations being conducted against these 2 punters, which would have revealed the amounts of bets placed by them[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3).

### MSC-900084-2022 and 4 Ors

16     The Prosecution submitted for a fine of $1,500 to be imposed in respect of each of the charges in MSC-900084-2022, MSC-900086-2022, MSC-900088-2022 and MSC-900095-2022 and a fine of $2,000 in respect of MSC-900091-2022 in view of the larger quantity of e-cigarette pods involved. The total fine is therefore $8,000.

17     In support of their submissions, the Prosecution tendered a table described as “Tiered Sentencing Framework for s 16 TCSA” based on the range of fines imposed in unreported precedent cases. The relevant portion of the table is set out below.

## Mitigation and Defence’s Submissions on Sentence

### MAC-900260-2022

19     The Defence submitted for **the prescribed minimum fine of $20,000** to be imposed in respect of the charge under s 9(1)(e) of the RGA.

20     The Defence submitted that the harm level in this case was in the lowest end of the low range under the _Khoo Moy Seen_ framework. The Defence cited the low bet value in this case and the absence of any syndicate involvement or involvement of a transnational element. The Defence also submitted that there was no difficulty in detecting the Accused’s offence.

21     In terms of the level culpability, the Defence submitted similarly that it was in the lowest end of the low range. The Defence submitted that there was no planning and premeditation on the part of the Accused given that the Accused had merely requested for an account from Johnny for purposes of placing personal bets. With regards to creating the punter account for his father, the Accused had done so to stop his father from frequently pestering him to place bets on his behalf. There was also a low level of sophistication on the part of the Accused as he had not broadcasted or messaged anyone to place bets with him.

22     In relation to the bets that the Accused had placed on behalf of the other 2 punters, namely his aunt and his friend, the Defence humbly submits that this was done in a capacity of a “helpful punter” albeit his account was that of an agent. The Accused had not opened any punter accounts for them. The Accused also did not work for any syndicate and had not actively secured more punters. The Accused also made little personal gain as the bets placed through him were occasional and small. The Accused had also returned any profit made through his father’s punter account to his father.

23     As for the duration of offending, the Defence submitted that only the period between 9 to 23 June 2021 should be considered as that was the period the punter account created by the Accused for his father was used. The period between October 2020 to 8 June 2021 should be disregarded as the Accused had merely used the agent account that is equivalent to that as a punter.

24     The Defence drew comparison with the factual matrixes in _Khoo Moy Seen_ and other precedent cases which involved more aggravating factors. In particular, the Defence cited the case of _PP v Tai Li Hui Matthew_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 39</span> (“Tai”) in support. In _Tai’s_ case, the accused was a worker who facilitated the complainant to play an online poker game via an application called “PPPoker”. Anyone who wished to participate in the poker game would inform the accused, tell the accused their account name, and transfer money into the accused’s account and the accused would tell his “boss” about it. The “boss” would then transfer gaming credits to the players’ accounts based on how much money they transferred to the accused’s bank account. The Court considered the following factors in sentencing the accused to 1 week’s imprisonment :

> (a)     The accused facilitated for the purchase of credits for the complainant to play online poker multiple times over the course of three days;

> (b)     The accused’s role was merely a worker in this scheme;

> (c)     The level of sophistication was low as he messaged people in a general chat group and waited for a response from interested parties (as opposed to actively recruiting them into joining his scheme);

> (d)     The accused was involved in the offending for a short period of time; and

> (e)     The accused does not appear to have derived personal gain from this scheme.

25     The Defence submitted that the custodial threshold had not been crossed in the present case. In support of their submission, the Defence tendered a list of unreported precedents where only fines were imposed.

26     The Defence further submitted that the Accused was working as a real estate agent and that any custodial sentence would inevitably shatter his career prospects and be crushing on him.

### MSC-900084-2022 and 4 Ors

27     The Defence submitted that the appropriate starting sentence for the HSA charges should be a fine of S$1,500.00 each in respect of MSC-900084-2022, MSC-900086-2022, MSC-900088-2022 and MSC-900095-2022, and a fine of S$2,000.00 in respect of MSC-900091-2022. The Defence further submitted that a downward adjustment of $500 be applied for each charge in view of the mitigating factors which included the Accused’s remorse, his early plea of guilt, his co-operation with investigations and his status as a first-offender.

## Sentencing Considerations

### MAC-900260-2022

28     Section 9(1) of the RGA states:

> **Providing unlawful remote gambling service for another**

> 9(1)  A person (called an agent) who, inside or outside Singapore —

>> (a)    organises, manages or supervises remote gambling by others in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent, which may include —

>>> (i)    inviting others to gamble using remote communication in accordance with those arrangements; or

>>> (ii)   placing, making, receiving or accepting bets using remote communication in accordance with those arrangements;

>> (b)    distributes a prize offered in remote gambling by others in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent;

>> (c)    distributes money or money’s worth paid or staked by others in remote gambling in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent;

>> (d)    facilitates participation by others in remote gambling in accordance with arrangements made by a principal of the agent, which may include allowing a person to participate in such remote gambling; or

>> (e)       assists in any conduct described in paragraph (a), (b), (c) or (d),

> and as a result facilitates one or more individuals to commit an offence under section 8, shall be guilty of an offence and shall be liable on conviction to a fine of not less than $20,000 and not more than $200,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 5 years or to both.

#### Level of harm

29     In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court held, under the five-step sentencing framework (see paragraph 11), that in determining the level of harm, the court may have regard to the following offence-specific factors:

> (a)     the aggregate value of the bets involved;

> (b)     the involvement of a syndicate;

> (c)     the involvement of a transnational element; and

> (d)     the difficulty of detection.

30     The total bet value which could be determined by police investigations was $418.10. This was in respect of the betting account issued by the Accused to his father and for bets made between 9 to 23 June 2021, a period of about 14 days. It was clear, however, from the SOF that the Accused had collected bets from 2 other punters. In the mitigation plea, the Accused had also disclosed that he had created the punter account for his father as the Accused got annoyed that his father had frequently contacted him to place bets on his behalf. Given these factors and having considered the fact that the Accused had operated his agent account for a period of about 8 months between October 2020 to 22 June 2021, it would be logical to infer that the actual bet value would have been higher than the amount which could be determined by police investigations.

31     I acknowledged, however, that the ascertained bet value before this court was $418.10 and while it may be inferred from the facts that the actual bet value was higher, it remains impossible to even estimate how much higher the actual bet value might be.

32     According to the SOF, investigations had revealed that “Johnny” operated an unlawful remote gambling syndicate and had several syndicate members operating under him. The Accused had also admitted to having accepted “Johnny’s” offer to operate an agent account and operating the agent account between October 2020 and 22 June 2021 in accordance with arrangements by “Johnny”. There was, as such, clear involvement of a syndicate in this case.

33     In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court held that there was some difficulty in detection where the placing of bets was done on the online sphere, rendering it inherently more difficult to detect. The bets in the present case were placed online.

34     Having regard to all these factors, I was of the view that the harm caused was in the lower end of the low range. This would be consistent with _Khoo Moy Seen_. In that case, the total bet value was $12,010.40 and there was involvement of a syndicate and difficulty in detection as well. The High Court had assessed the harm caused to be in the middle of the low range.

#### Level of culpability

35     As regards culpability, the following factors would be relevant:

> (a)     the degree of planning and premeditation;

> (b)     the level of sophistication;

> (c)     the offender’s role;

> (d)     personal gain; and

> (e)     the duration of offending

36     The Accused had knowingly accepted the offer of an agent account from “Johnny” and had operated the account in accordance with arrangements with “Johnny”. It was in fact the Accused who had told his friend “Andy” he wanted to have an account for unlawful 4D remote gambling and had asked “Andy” whether he could introduce anyone to him. “Andy” then introduced “Johnny” to the Accused subsequently. The Accused had also operated the account for a relatively long period of 8 months.

37     Notwithstanding, I note that investigations had revealed that the Accused had only 2 other punters betting through him besides his father throughout the entire offending period. The level of sophistication was also relatively low. The Accused had merely placed bets from his punters using his own account. With regards to the punter account issued to his father, the Accused had also not taken any steps to avoid detection such as providing a false or misleading name for the account.

38     In terms of personal gain, while this could not be determined by investigations, I was of the view that it could be inferred from the SOF that the Accused had made some gains, albeit which amount had not been determined.

39     The Accused’s culpability in this case was clearly lower than that of _Khoo Moy Seen_ where the accused had actively acted as an agent and had 15 punters placing bets through her. The total bet value of $12,010.40 was substantial and the accused stood to earn about $1,000 in rebates.

40     In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court had assessed the culpability level to be on the higher end of the low range, at least. Drawing guidance from the case, I was of the view that the Accused’s culpability in the present case fell on the lower end of the low range.

#### The indicative sentencing range and the starting point within the indicative sentencing range

41     Given that both the harm and culpability levels were at the lower end of the low range, the indicative starting sentence would be a fine of at least $20,000 and/or a short term of imprisonment.

#### Whether the custodial threshold had been crossed

42     The Defence had submitted that a custodial sentence would not be appropriate in the present case. While the Defence had tendered a list of unreported precedents where only fines were imposed, it is notable that the list contained merely the charge and case numbers and the sentence meted out. In the absence of any further information, it would be impossible for the court to draw any guidance from the sentences set out in the list. It is well-established that unreported decisions are of limited precedential value given that they are unreasoned, and it is therefore not possible to discern what had weighed on the mind of the sentencing judge (_Janardana Jayasankarr v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 4 SLR 1288</span> at \[13(b)\]). In the present case, not only were the precedents cited by the Defence unreasoned, even the facts and particulars of the charges were absent. Notably, the precedent cases all date back to before _Khoo Moy Seen_. I place no weight, as such, on the unreported precedents cited by the Defence.

43     Although the factual matrix in the present case was less egregious than that of _Khoo Moy Seen_, the Accused’s knowing participation as an agent in an unlawful remote gambling syndicate warranted, in my view, a custodial sentence notwithstanding the low levels of harm and culpability. The need for general deterrence against illegal remote gambling remains a key sentencing consideration in the present case. A mere fine would not be effective, in my view, in achieving the objective of general deterrence.

44     In _Tai’s_ case (see paragraph 24 above), a case for which the Defence has submitted that the Accused’s level of culpability in the present case was equivalent to, the Senior District Judge had sentenced the accused to 1 week’s imprisonment “given the strong need for general deterrence in respect of remote gambling offences”.

45     In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court had also held at \[34\] that,

> “…a mere fine would not adequately serve the ends of deterrence. …Such illegal online gambling activities are also inherently difficult to detect, and the temptation for punters and agents alike are ever-present given the ease and allure of making a quick profit. This may be contrasted with brick-and-mortar gambling where some form of structural and regulatory control, such as prohibitions of access, can be more easily put into place. As such, a sufficiently stringent sentence is necessary, both to deter like-minded individuals from engaging in the appellant’s conduct, and to deter further offending by the appellant…” 

#### Appropriateness of a fine

46     The imposition of a fine in addition to a term of imprisonment would be appropriate in the present case. In _Khoo Moy Seen_, the High Court held at \[32\] that “a fine in addition to the imprisonment term is necessary to negate the profit motive of remote gambling activities”. Although the total bet value determined in this case was relatively low, it could be readily inferred that the Accused had made some gains. The imposition of a fine in addition to a term of imprisonment would therefore be appropriate.

47     After having carefully considered the parties’ respective submissions, the facts and circumstances of the present case, and drawing guidance from the reported precedent cases, in particular _Khoo Moy Seen_ and _Tai_, I was of the view that it would be appropriate to impose a sentence of 2 week’s imprisonment in addition to the minimum prescribed fine.

#### Adjustment for offender-specific factors

48     The Accused is a first offender and has pleaded guilty. I noted, however, that the Accused had failed to render full co-operation during investigations. By refusing to disclose the details of the 2 punters who had placed bets through him, the Accused had prevented investigations from being carried out against these punters. More importantly, it had prevented the police from unravelling the full extent of the Accused’s offending. This was particularly in respect of the actual total bet value involved and the commission or profit he had gained from these bets.

49     The Accused also faced 15 charges under s 16(2) of the TCASA for which he had pleaded guilty to 5 counts and consented to the remaining counts being TIC.

50     In the circumstances, I was of the view that there were no merits justifying any downward adjustment to the sentence.

### MSC-900084-2022 and 4 Ors

51     I noted that the starting sentences submitted by the Defence were similar to the sentences proposed by the Prosecution. The only issue as such was whether it would be appropriate to apply a downward adjustment of $500 per charge as submitted by the Defence.

52     Although the Accused was a first offender and had pleaded guilty, there were a total of 15 charges under s 16(2) TCASA against him of which 10 had been TIC.

53     Given the substantial number of charges involved, I was of the view that there were no merits justifying any downward adjustment in the sentence.

## Sentence Imposed

54     Having considered all of the above, the Accused was sentenced to **2 week’s imprisonment and fine of $20,000 in default 4 weeks’ imprisonment** in respect of the charge in MAC 900260-2022.

55     He was sentenced to **$1,500 fine in default 6 days’ imprisonment** in respect of each of the 4 charges in MSC-900084-2022, MSC-900086-2022, MSC-900088-2022 and MSC-900095-2022, and **$2,000 fine in default 8 days’ imprisonment** in respect of the charge in MSC-900091-2022.

56     The total sentence was therefore **2 weeks’ imprisonment and a total fine of $28,000 in default 4 weeks and 32 days’ imprisonment**.

57     The Accused being dissatisfied with the decision had lodged an appeal against his sentence. He is currently on bail pending appeal.
